Then $AP = \frac{PS}{\sin \alpha} = \frac{3}{\sin \alpha},$ so
\[BP = \frac{3}{\sin \alpha} \sin \phi = \frac{3}{\sin \alpha} \cos \theta,\]and
\[CP = \frac{3}{\sin \alpha} \cos \phi = \frac{3}{\sin \alpha} \sin \theta.\]Then by the Law of Cosines on triangles $BPQ$ and $CPQ,$
\begin{align*}
x^2 &= BP^2 + PQ^2 - 2 BP \cdot PQ \cos \beta + BQ^2 \\
&= \frac{9 \cos^2 \theta}{\sin^2 \alpha} + 1 - 2 \cdot \frac{3 \cos \theta}{\sin \alpha} \cos \beta + \frac{9 \sin^2 \theta}{\sin^2 \alpha}, \\
x^2 &= CP^2 + PQ^2 - 2 CP \cdot PQ \cos \gamma + CQ^2 \\
&= \frac{9 \sin^2 \theta}{\sin^2 \alpha} + 1 - 2 \cdot \frac{3 \sin \theta}{\sin \alpha} \cos \gamma + \frac{9 \cos^2 \theta}{\sin^2 \alpha}.
\end{align*}Adding these equations, we get
\[2x^2 = 2 + \frac{9}{\sin^2 \alpha} (\cos^2 \theta + \sin^2 \theta) - 6 \cdot \frac{3}{\sin^2 \alpha} \cos \theta \cos \beta - 6 \cdot \frac{3}{\sin^2 \alpha} \sin \theta \cos \gamma.\]Since $\triangle ABC$ is equilateral, $\alpha + \beta + \gamma = 60^\circ,$ so $\cos \gamma = \cos (60^\circ - \beta) = \frac{1}{2} \sin \beta.$  Similarly, $\cos \beta = \cos (60^\circ - \gamma) = \frac{1}{2} \sin \gamma.$  Hence,
\begin{align*}
2x^2 &= 2 + \frac{9}{\sin^2 \alpha} - 9 \cdot \frac{3}{\sin^2 \alpha} \cos \theta \sin \beta - 9 \cdot \frac{3}{\sin^2 \alpha} \sin \theta \cos \gamma \\
&= 2 + \frac{9}{\sin^2 \alpha} - \frac{27}{\sin^2 \alpha} (\cos \theta \sin \beta + \sin \theta \cos \gamma) \\
&= 2 + \frac{9}{\sin^2 \alpha} - \frac{27}{\sin^2 \alpha} \sin (\beta + \theta) \\
&= 2 + \frac{9}{\sin^2 \alpha} - \frac{27}{\sin^2 \alpha} \sin (60^\circ - \alpha) \\
&= 2 + \frac{9}{\sin^2 \alpha} - \frac{27}{4 \sin^2 \alpha}.
\end{align*}Then
\[\frac{27}{4 \sin^2 \alpha} = 2 + \frac{9}{\sin^2 \alpha} - 2x^2.\]Since $\sin^2 \alpha + \cos^2 \alpha = 1,$
\begin{align*}
\frac{27}{4 (1 - \cos^2 \alpha)} &= 2 + \frac{9}{1 - \cos^2 \alpha} - 2x^2 \\
\frac{27}{4 \cos^2 \alpha} &= 2 + \frac{9}{\cos^2 \alpha} - 2x^2.
\end{align*}Let $t = \cos^2 \alpha.$  Then
\[\frac{27}{4t} = 2 + \frac{9}{t} - 2x^2.\]Solving for $t,$ we find $t = \frac{27}{8 + 8x^2}.$

