Then $PQ = BP \sin \theta = s/2 \cdot \sin \theta = 1$, $PR = BP \cos \theta = s/2 \cdot \cos \theta = 2$, and $PS = AP = s/2 \cdot \sin (60^\circ - \theta) = s/2 \cdot \cos \theta = 3$.  Solving $\sin \theta = 2/s$ and $\cos \theta = 4/s$ gives
\[\tan \theta = \frac{\sin \theta}{\cos \theta} = \frac{1}{2}.\]Then $\tan (60^\circ - \theta) = \sqrt{3} - \tan \theta = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},$ so
\[s = 2BP = 2 \cdot \frac{PQ}{\sin \theta} = 4 \quad \Longrightarrow \quad AB = \boxed{4}.\]

